Part 1

The bulldozer was yellow, with a dented steel bucket that had *Escorts* painted in red letters on the side.

It sat near the shelter gate for three days before it started working.

The driver spent the first two days sleeping in the cabin, his legs dangling out of the open door, his shirt thrown over the steering wheel to block the sun.

On the third morning, the municipal junior engineer arrived in a jeep.

He didn't get down.

He simply waved a blue paper toward Sarita, who was standing near the well holding a plastic bucket.

"Road widening," he shouted over the jeep's engine. "Clear the rooms by twelve."

"We have fourteen patients," Sarita said. "Three cannot walk."

"The order was signed in March, sister. The contractor is paying daily rent on the machine. Twelve o'clock."

He turned the jeep.

The dust from the tyres settled on the drumstick trees, turning the green leaves a dull grey.

Vikram had tried to call Rohan from the post office phone.

He had dialled the office number twice.

Both times, the receptionist's voice had come through the static, polite and unyielding.

"Ahuja saab is in a board meeting. Leave a message."

"Tell him it's Vikram."

"Yes, sir. I have noted it."

He didn't call again.

At eleven-thirty, the steel bucket of the bulldozer touched the courtyard wall.

A low, grating sound of mortar giving way.

Ananya stood near the kitchen door, holding her wooden horse and the notebook with the white chalk drawings.

She wasn't crying.

She looked at the machine with the same unblinking curiosity she had used for the equations.

"It is very loud," she said.

"Yes," Vikram said.

"Will they break the well too?"

"Yes."

She nodded.

She walked to his side, her small hand finding the pocket of his faded cotton shirt, holding onto the fabric.

"Where will we sleep tonight?"

"Kolkata," Vikram said.

---

The train was the Howrah Express.

They had three third-class compartments, the tickets bought with the last eight thousand rupees Sarita had in the shelter tin box.

The patients sat near the windows, their thin faces drawing the attention of the vendors selling tea and peanuts at every station.

An old woman with a severe cough kept her face covered with her saree border.

A passenger from the middle berth looked down, saw her thin wrists, and moved his luggage to the upper rack.

He didn't say anything.

Neither did Sarita.

She sat opposite Vikram, her forehead pressed against the iron bars of the window.

The fever had returned.

Her skin was hot to the touch, dry and paper-thin.

"The house belongs to my husband's uncle," she said. Her voice was thin, dry like the breeze outside. "He died in ninety-two. The sons went to Delhi. Nobody has lived there for twenty years."

"Is there a well?" Vikram asked.

"A municipal tap," she said. "In the courtyard. And three big neem trees. The leaves are good for the heat."

She closed her eyes.

"It is in Bagbazar. Near the river. The wind smells of wet jute and river mud."

Vikram looked at the passing fields.

The green paddy of Odisha was slowly giving way to the grey marshlands of Bengal.

The wheels of the train kept up their rhythmic, metallic clank.

*Fourteen hundred.*

*Fourteen hundred.*

*Fourteen hundred.*

The number didn't have the same sound anymore.

It was just noise.

---

The house in Bagbazar had a large wooden door that had swollen from the monsoon damp, refusing to open more than a foot.

Vikram had to shoulder it twice, the old iron lock cracking inside the wood with a sound like dry bone breaking.

The air inside was thick, smelling of bat droppings, wet lime, and the cold, unventilated damp of twenty years of shadow.

The plaster had fallen off the walls in large, curved sheets, showing the thin red brick underneath.

A courtyard sat in the middle, three neem trees growing wild, their roots lifting the old stone tiles at angles.

An old marble nameplate near the entrance read: *Sen family. 1924.*

Ananya walked in first, her sandals making clean prints in the thick grey dust that covered the floor.

"It has many rooms," she said.

"Eleven," Sarita said, leaning against the door frame to catch her breath.

She looked at the courtyard, at the dry neem leaves that had piled up in the corners.

"The tap is in the corner," she said, pointing to a rusted iron pipe rising from the stone.

Vikram went to the tap.

He turned the handle.

A dry squeak. Then a thin stream of orange, rust-stained water came out, sputtering before it went clear and cold.

He drew a handful.

It tasted of iron and river sand.

He washed his face.

The water felt different from the Odisha well.

It was heavier. Older.

Sarita sat on the lowest step of the verandah, her head resting against the wooden pillar that had been eaten away by termites near the base.

"We will start with the front room," she said. "Sweep the dust. The patients are waiting at the crossing with the luggage."

Vikram picked up a broom he'd bought at the station.

The bamboo bristles were stiff, scratching the old stone floor with a sharp, dry sound.

Ananya sat near the well tap, setting her three-legged horse on a clean stone she'd wiped with her skirt.

It stood.

"See?" she said, pointing. "It works here too."

Vikram began to sweep.

The dust rose in the afternoon sun, turning the shafts of light into columns of moving, grey sand.

He swept the first room.

Then the second.

His hands, already hard from the well rope of Odisha, didn't feel the bamboo handle anymore.

He had left the boardrooms.

He had left the big white cars.

He had left the name that opened gates.

But as he swept the dust of twenty years out of the Sen family house, the iron-tasting water of the Bagbazar tap felt like exactly enough to keep him where he was.

[End of Part 1]
